defaultThe proposal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies defaultshould only be paid for work done on the case if the Court grants permission for the application to proceeddefaultThe proposed changes to access to Judicial Review (JR) are likely to impact asylum seekers and refugees, as well as the charities who work with the
defaultm, far beyond that anticipated in the consultation.
default&#xa0;
defaultWork to research, prepare and present a JR is often substantial, especially to address concerns in the handling of the most complex asylum claims. If implemented, this proposal would act as a 
defaultdisincentive for providers to undertake JR work even where merits are established, as any work prior to permission being granted by the court would have to be undertaken pro bono. This will make it very difficult for people facing destitution to access JR,
default particularly to apply for urgent injunctions. It will also make it far more difficult to undertake strategic litigation work to test and develop the law, which by definition is work carried out at risk, with border line potential for success.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe govern
defaultment has emphasised that funding will remain in place for meritorious JRs, to be paid after the decision on merits; but few organisations will have the cash-flow resources to prepare a JR appropriately knowing that this work will not be recompensed for man
defaulty months. As 
defaultthe 
defaultI
defaultmmigration 
defaultL
defaultaw 
defaultP
defaultractitioners’ 
defaultA
defaultssociation
default 
default(ILPA) has argued recently
default, after a succession of cuts many 
defaultLegal Aid
default providers “cannot assume any more financial risk in their businesses”.
default In practice, it will become a lasting challenge to fun
defaultd upfront the work needed to file a JR, even where the merits of the case are immediately evident. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition
default, the underlying motive to sav
defaulte public expenditure is 
defaultquestionable when one takes into account the fact that weak cases are already refused perm
defaultission to proceed. This mechanism is already in place to protect the public purse and strikes a fair balance. In urgent cases the merits of the case need to be kept under ongoing assessment, but the final decision on whether to grant 
defaultLegal Aid
default always rests
default with the 
defaultLegal Aid
default Agency, not the provider. 
defaultRestricting access to JRs would have the effect of limiting essential access to justice, even where there is an overwhelming need to correct an error in a previous decision. Some of the most vulnerable asylum 
defaultseekers and refugees would be left without recourse to help to which they are entitled, including: 
default&#xa0;
defaultAsylum Aid is deeply concerned at this prospect. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHaving borne witness over many years to the flaws and shortcomings in asylum decision-making, and the regularity with which the Home Office acts in breach of its own policies and procedures, the use of JR is paramount where there are legitimate concerns th
defaultat the government has acted illegally or irrationally. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe government can maintain access to justice and more effectively save money by ensuring the Home Office takes a fair and competent approach to asylum claims earlier in the system. If the operation 
defaultof the asylum system is aligned with the policies already in place, recourse to an expensive JR process will rightly become an exceptional occurrence.
