defaultThe proposal that defaultLegal Aiddefault should be removed for all cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of successdefaultThere is a very real risk that, by removing 
defaultLegal Aid
default from cases which meet the ‘borderline’ criteria, the human rights needs of some asylum seekers will not be met. 
default&#xa0;
defaultW
defaulte share the concerns raised by ILPA in their response to the government’s consultation paper, where ILPA stated:
default&#xa0;
default[
defaultLegal Aid
default practitioners]
default are frequently in the position of challenging cases that they know will be hard to win, for example because there is
default settled law in the higher courts against them. It is frequently impossible fairly to judge the merits of a case before it has been prepared, which is why the borderline category is important.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is true of many of the complex asylum cases in which Asy
defaultlum Aid specialises, where particular expertise and time is required to identify the protection needs that ensure a case meets at least the ‘borderline’ criteria. If these cases are no longer funded, 
defaultsuch vulnerable clients
default will not enjoy access to justice
default. This is also the case for strategic litigation, which necessarily tests the law in areas which remain under development.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, it is our experience that some legal representatives are unable or unwilling to take on the most complex appeals and Ju
defaultdicial Reviews because of the unfunded hours of work required to demonstrate that they meet at least the ‘borderline’ criteria. In our 2011 
defaultUnsustainable
default research into women’s asylum claims, for example, half the women in our sample from Cardiff did not ha
defaultve legal representation on appeal, something likely related to the complexity of many gender-related asylum claims.
default&#xa0;
defaultDespite this, women’s claims are disproportionately likely to be overturned on appeal, indicating that 
defaultsome
default work at first assumed not be m
defaulteet ‘borderline’ criteria is nonetheless necessary to overturn poor initial Home Office decisions.
